   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB823_1817_06_12_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName>
                  <date when="1817-06-12"/>June 12. 1817 </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>
               Obedience is better than Sacrifice says<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. E.</persName> - And I deduce from thence the<lb/>
               corollary than executing commissions is<lb/>
               better than long answers to the letters which<lb/>
               convey them. I have just persuaded<lb/>
               the old lady to carry a box for you to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1"> M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.<lb/>
                  Hunter</persName>'s containing paper for all the roads<lb/>
               in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> - Sundry rulers and<lb/>
               M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> E's <del>m</del> valve. - My friend <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GallX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Galloway</persName>
               <lb/>
               the Machinist &amp; Engineer made the latter<lb/>
               article - He could not staunch either of<lb/>
               the patterns and I therefore allowed him<lb/>
               to fabricate a new article altogether which appears<lb/>
               to be very perfect. - There are two small cocks<lb/>
               with adjusting screws by which the slide (which<lb/>
               is made by his advice dovetail fashion) can be<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB823_1817_06_12_page02.jpg"/>            
               tightened to any degree of closeness - and<lb/>
               which will compensate for any <unclear>wear</unclear> -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>The cost however is great - I copy the<lb/>
               bill - To a Brass dovetail frame with a <choice>
                  <orig>gun .<lb/>
                  metal</orig>
                  <reg>gunmetal</reg>
               </choice> slide 6 <unclear>1/2</unclear> long &amp; 13/8 wide with cock and<lb/>
               screws. Connecting the friction roller (from the<lb/>
               old model) with screws &amp; for a valve<lb/>
               apparatus - £ 2 .. 14 -<lb/>
               A Copper oblong trough &amp; soldering<lb/>
               it to the brass frame - <hi rend="underline">9</hi>
               <lb/>
               £ 3 .. 3 -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName>'s Errata I carried the instant<lb/>
               I received them to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#St-Pauls-Churchyard_ENK">S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. Paul's</placeName> but two sheets<lb/>
               of the second edition were already<lb/>
               printed off - - The remainder of the<lb/>
               sheets will be corrected -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>  For <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1"> M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> E</persName>'s valuable remarks &amp; Errata<lb/>
               on my little work I am thankful, and<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB823_1817_06_12_page03.jpg"/>
               <hi rend="underline">they</hi> are in good time for a second<lb/>
               edition - to which I fancy it has<lb/>
               but little chance of attaining - What<lb/>
               a favourable review may do is a hope<lb/>
               I indulge for the publisher's sake - and<lb/>
               that <del>such</del> a review is <unclear>brewing</unclear> I have<lb/>
               indistinctly heard<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FxxxJ1"> M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> J L F</persName>'s speech has been published<lb/>
                 but <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RomiS1">Sir Sam. Romilly</persName>  who I met at<lb/>
                 dinner at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ManeX1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                  <unclear>Manet's</unclear>
               </persName> and <add>of</add> whom I<lb/>
               asked the questions, says it made no<lb/>
               impression whatever on the house when<lb/>
               delivered.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauA1">Alicia</persName> joins with me in <unclear>best</unclear>
               <lb/>
               thanks for your <unclear>fables</unclear>, and both my<lb/>
               little boys who already point to your<lb/>
               picture and repeat your difficult<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB823_1817_06_12_page04.jpg"/>   
               name, will have an additional <choice>
                  <orig>ob-<lb/>
               ligation </orig>
                  <reg>obligation</reg>
               </choice>to your labours - common<lb/>
               indeed to other children who can purchase<lb/>
               them - but the <unclear>greatest</unclear> they can owe<lb/>
               you and which cannot be purchased<lb/>
               is for the improvement of their father<lb/>
               by your example and advice<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <figure>
                  <figDesc>Drawing of a hand with pointed index finger.</figDesc>
               </figure> For <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Your directions have been obeyed<lb/>
               and 5 were quite sufficient to send<lb/>
               to the <del>Hill</del>Chapel mountain - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HxxxX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.<lb/>
               H.</persName> does not <del>the</del> know how to calculate<lb/>
               any extra expense for expediting <title ref="./Workography.xml#Harri1">Harrington</title>
               <lb/>
               but he has promised to tell me candidly<lb/>
               when he settles with the printer - Of the<lb/>
               two sheets which were cancelled from the<lb/>
               change in the division of the volumes <del/>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB823_1817_06_12_page05.jpg"/>  
               you are already aware. -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Harri1">Ormond &amp; <choice>
                     <orig>Har.</orig>
                     <reg>Harrington&gt;</reg>
                  </choice>
               </title> are advertised for<lb/>
               publication, but I am sorry to find<lb/>
               that it is impossible to get them out<lb/>
               by the time for which I stood sponsor.<lb/>
               - The 25<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> is to usher them into the<lb/>
               world - and considerable expectation<lb/>
               is already excited - This I can learn<lb/>
               but I cannot learn the public feeling<lb/>
               about the Dramas as my connexion<lb/>
               with the firm is too notorious to<lb/>
               allow people either to praise or<lb/>
               blame freely -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I cannot discover who the principle<lb/>
               writers are in the <title ref="./Workography.xml#BritRe1">British Review</title> - the<lb/>
               work is however known to be in the<lb/>
               hands of what is called the High Church<lb/>
               <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB823_1817_06_12_page06.jpg"/>         
               as opposed to the Methodists. -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I have sent for N<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>. 17 to read<lb/>
               the article on Metrology -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <figure>
                  <figDesc>Drawing of a hand with pointed index finger.</figDesc>
               </figure>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. E.</persName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Your little commission has been likewise<lb/>
               executed - it cost 2½ Guineas but<lb/>
               turned out entirely fruitless -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I went to the fabricator of <unclear>Darwin's</unclear>
               <lb/>
               pills to complain of their spicy flavour<lb/>
               - he told me that several gentlemen<lb/>
               had complained of the smell &amp; taste<lb/>
               of the oil of aniseed with which they<lb/>
               were made up - and that to suit<lb/>
               their palates Oil of Cinnamon was<lb/>
               substituted - which made no kind<lb/>
               of difference in the essential effect<lb/>
                  of the compound - but if <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> E.</persName> likes<lb/>
               <pb n="7" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB823_1817_06_12_page07.jpg"/>        
               it he will make him up a box with<lb/>
               the old materials.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I asked at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ColbH1">Coulburns</persName>'s about <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MorgS1">Lady<lb/>
               Morgan</persName>'s book but the only reply he<lb/>
               would vouchsafe was - "It is not out<lb/>
               yet Sir" - He is a paltry fellow<lb/>
               And his <title ref="./Workography.xml#LitGa1">Literary Gazette</title> is -<lb/>
               but I won't say what till I see how<lb/>
               he treats <title ref="./Workography.xml#Karam1">Kara.</title>
               <lb/>
               I don't know nor<lb/>
               have yet seen <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ChapX1">Chapple</persName> or his book -<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StopX1">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>
                  <unclear>Stofford</unclear>
               </persName> is the very man you recollect<lb/>
               at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Bristol_ENK">Bristol</placeName> - I have now answered<lb/>
               all your questions, and the only commission<lb/>
               unnoticed is <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GillX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Gillock</persName>'s whom I have<lb/>
               not yet been able to meet as he lives in<lb/>
               the Country and only comes to his office<lb/>
               <pb n="8" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB823_1817_06_12_page08.jpg"/>          
               in the morning. - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauA1">Alicia</persName> and the<lb/>
               boys are all well - Pray have any<lb/>
               of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentJ1">
                  <unclear>Bentham's</unclear>
               </persName> late publications been<lb/>
               read at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Etown</placeName>? - And how are they liked?<lb/>
               They are a little trop fort I should<lb/>
               imagine for the taste of the Attorney<lb/>
               General -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>You seem in a miserable<lb/>
               way in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> - but we are not<lb/>
                  on roses. For <figure>
                  <figDesc>Drawing of a hand with pointed index finger.</figDesc>
               </figure>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>In a long deal box particularly<lb/>
               recommended to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hunter's</persName>
               <lb/>
               protection and through him to the<lb/>
               carriers sailors &amp; agents you<lb/>
               will find the following articles<lb/>
               <del/> for you<lb/>
            </p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back> </back>
